docs.abstract: In 1981, Anthony Kline helped send a juvenile offender to prison for four decades. This year, in a twist of fate, he had a chance to decide her case again.
docs.snippet: In 1981, Anthony Kline helped send a juvenile offender to prison for four decades. This year, in a twist of fate, he had a chance to decide her case again.
docs.lead_paragraph: None of Anthony Kline’s colleagues had ever seen it happen. The most senior justice on California’s First District Court of Appeal, Kline was asking to be transferred to the juvenile bench, at the advanced age of 83. Juvenile was the scrappy place you started a career, not the triumphant place you ended one. But after four decades in appeals, Kline was feeling estranged from real life. He wanted to spend a year in juvie before retiring.

headline.main: The Judge and the Case That Came Back to Haunt Him

docs.abstract: Taylor Swift, the pop megastar who has increasingly leveraged her fame and platform to weigh in on political matters and social causes, announced Wednesday that she would support Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Senator Kamala Harris in the presidential election.
docs.lead_paragraph: Taylor Swift, the pop megastar who has increasingly leveraged her fame and platform to weigh in on political matters and social causes, announced Wednesday that she would support Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Senator Kamala Harris in the presidential election.

headline.main: Taylor Swift, leaning further into politics, endorses Joe Biden and Kamala Harris.

docs.abstract: A forceful campaign by federal law enforcement in Portland, Ore., has prompted an escalation in tactics from some protesters, while others wonder whether they are losing their focus.
docs.snippet: A forceful campaign by federal law enforcement in Portland, Ore., has prompted an escalation in tactics from some protesters, while others wonder whether they are losing their focus.
docs.lead_paragraph: PORTLAND, Ore. — Minutes before midnight on Sunday, the first firework of the evening screeched low over the heads of protesters gathered in Portland, Ore., sprinkling them with white flecks of light and ricocheting into the courthouse that has become a symbol of an unwelcome federal incursion into a local outcry over police brutality.

headline.main: Peaceful Protesters With ‘Room for Rage’ Sympathize With Aggressive Tactics
headline.print_headline: Joy, Rage and Suspicion: Complex Alchemy Shapes a Protest Movement

byline.original: By Kate Conger, Thomas Fuller and Mike Baker

docs.abstract: Kahlik Grier, 16, was fatally shot in a random encounter in the stairwell of his Bronx apartment building, the police said.
docs.snippet: Kahlik Grier, 16, was fatally shot in a random encounter in the stairwell of his Bronx apartment building, the police said.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was a routine school night for Kahlik Grier, a 16-year-old student in the Bronx. After a day of online classes, he had Chinese takeout with his mother. Then he made his way to a friend’s apartment three stories below to play video games.

headline.main: A Teenager Went 3 Floors Down to Play Video Games. He Never Came Home.
headline.print_headline: Teenager Is Shot Dead in Stairwell of His Building, as a Wave of Violence Continues

docs.abstract: House of Yes was a revolution in New York nightlife: A space at once wild and safe, challenging and inclusive. Can it ever come back?
docs.snippet: House of Yes was a revolution in New York nightlife: A space at once wild and safe, challenging and inclusive. Can it ever come back?
docs.lead_paragraph: It was just a year ago that Jacquelyn Feliciano and Jonathan McDonald were swinging upside down through the sticky, neon-colored air at House of Yes.

headline.main: It Had Aerialists, Fire Eaters and Glitter. Is Brooklyn’s Wildest Party Over?
headline.print_headline: Pining for a Brooklyn Club’s Comeback

byline.original: By Julia Carmel and Mohamed Sadek

docs.abstract: As a Black designer in the 1990s, he was heralded by insiders and overlooked by the fashion system. So he created his own.
docs.snippet: As a Black designer in the 1990s, he was heralded by insiders and overlooked by the fashion system. So he created his own.
docs.lead_paragraph: For the veteran fashion designer Byron Lars, who was named “rookie of the year” by Women’s Wear Daily in 1991, fashion moments never stop.

headline.print_headline: Byron Lars Is Still Here, Heralded And Hardy

docs.abstract: Vauhxx Booker said a group of white men surrounded him, pinned him against a tree and threatened to “get a noose” after he and his friends had gathered near Lake Monroe.
docs.snippet: Vauhxx Booker said a group of white men surrounded him, pinned him against a tree and threatened to “get a noose” after he and his friends had gathered near Lake Monroe.
docs.lead_paragraph: The F.B.I. is investigating a confrontation between a Black man and a group of white men who pinned him against a tree at an Indiana lake over the Fourth of July weekend, after video of the episode drew broad condemnation.

headline.main: F.B.I. to Investigate Case of Black Man Pinned by White Man in Indiana

docs.abstract: In an interview, the recently crowned N.B.A. champion discussed the work of More Than a Vote, a collective of athletes trying to combat misinformation among Black communities before Election Day.
docs.snippet: In an interview, the recently crowned N.B.A. champion discussed the work of More Than a Vote, a collective of athletes trying to combat misinformation among Black communities before Election Day.
docs.lead_paragraph: More Than a Vote, the collective of athletes headlined by the basketball star LeBron James, on Wednesday will introduce its final political push before Election Day, a rapid response and advertisement operation meant to combat the spread of misinformation among younger Black voters.

headline.main: LeBron James on Black Voter Participation, Misinformation and Trump
headline.print_headline: James on Black Voter Participation, Misinformation and the President

docs.abstract: Bobby White was celebrated as the “Basketball Cop” after millions saw a video of him shooting hoops with local teenagers. A recording from two years earlier shows him throwing a young Black man on the hood of his car during an arrest.
docs.snippet: Bobby White was celebrated as the “Basketball Cop” after millions saw a video of him shooting hoops with local teenagers. A recording from two years earlier shows him throwing a young Black man on the hood of his car during an arrest.
docs.lead_paragraph: Aahtrell Johnson remembered the police car rolling up, just before he was about to take his shot at the basket under the pine trees. It was 2016, and his neighbor had called 911, complaining that he was getting loud in the street. A white officer named Bobby White had been sent to respond.

headline.main: The Cop Was the Hero in One Viral Video. Another Told a Different Story.
headline.print_headline: Video Shatters Public’s Image Of Hoops Cop

docs.abstract: The chief executive of Apple, which was sued by the gaming company Epic, said his company had invested heavily on security and had lowered some fees in its App Store.
docs.snippet: The chief executive of Apple, which was sued by the gaming company Epic, said his company had invested heavily on security and had lowered some fees in its App Store.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tim Cook, testifying on Friday in a trial that could undermine Apple’s efforts to fend off growing scrutiny of its power, defended his business from accusations that it hurt app makers while on the hunt to expand its profits.

headline.main: In Antitrust Trial, Tim Cook Argues Apple Doesn’t Hurt App Makers
headline.print_headline: Apple C.E.O. Takes Stand In App Trial

byline.original: By Jack Nicas, Erin Griffith and Kellen Browning
